Freedom's Fury is a documentary on the 1956 Olympic semifinal water polo match between Hungary  and Russia  released at 7 September 2006. The documentary tells the story of the young star of the Hungarian Olympic waterpolo team, Ervin Zador, who finds himself the unwitting focal point of one of the most politicized sports matches ever played, popularly known as the Blood in the Water match. The journey of Zador and the Hungarian waterpolo team to 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne becomes the films through-line as &quot;Freedom's Fury&quot; explores the larger human tragedy of Hungarian Revolution of 1956. After the match Zador and half his teammates decided to defect rather than return to the oppression in their homeland.

In the final act, the documentary also touches on how the Hungarian Revolution become a symbol of freedom and impacted the collapse of communism in 1989.

